	     <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=32254><span id= >Nixoh</span></a><br><span id=notbold>484 posts<br><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent [4.63]</td><td valign=top class=mform width=100%><p>I guess it depends on where your AA are, but if you have 215 STR and it's routinely maxed by buffs you either haven't raised your caps or you're getting some amazing buffage.<br><br>Now, I play a necro for the most part, so I would never have a high STR, but even I'm drooling over this for the STA/CHA/AC/HP/mana. Most NEC don't know this, but CHA actually matters to you. I've heard that low CHA is good for fear, and that's fine, but I almost never fear in anything larger than a duo group.<br><br>On raids, if I do anything that needs CHA, it's Screaming Terror, and while CHA has no bearing on ST landing, it *does* change the mem-wipe percentage a LOT. In my own testing against the 50th level skelly quest mob in BW, I was able to go from about a 10-20% to around 30% mem-wipe rate on him for ST with only a small (30ish points) change in my CHA. In a raid where you're wiping mobs to defend the ENC as they AE mez the incoming hordes, this difference means that you live quite a bit longer.<br><br>In AC, I managed to spot-mez long enough that our chanter kept the whole raid alive with only 3 deaths when one of our party accidentally pulled about 20 mobs and a mini-boss at once. It was truely an example of what a raid full of people who know their classes and their jobs well can do.<br><br>It also goes to show that every stat has it's role and the conventional wisdom (low CHA for NEC) isn't always wise....<br></p>&nbsp;<br><span class=sm>----------------------------</span><br>You gain experience!<br>The Goblin Warlord hits YOU for 50 points!<br></td></tr>
